    <h4>Background</h4>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="large-6 columns">
        <p>The United Nations <a href="http://www.ohchr.org/en/professionalinterest/pages/crc.aspx" target="_blank">Convention on the Rights of the Child</a> (signed in 1989) set into stone several rights that apply to all children anywhere in the world, no matter their circumstance.  Interestingly enough, the United States was one of two UN member states (at the time) that was not a party to this human rights treaty.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="large-6 columns">
        <p>Several of these rights pertain to adoption.  While it's never explicitly stated, behind many of these rights lies the notion that children deserve to know their background.  Whether it has to do with biology, religion, ethnic identity, or any other category, children deserve to know their history and their roots.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

