  <div class="large-7 columns">
    <h4 class="subheader">The Problem</h4>

    <p>Adoption in the United States, aside from some overall federal legislation, is primarily left up to the state.  They have the right to determine if closed adoptions (an adoption process where there is no interaction of any kind between birth parents and prospective adoptive families) are fully closed, or if there's some exchange of information.  Some states allow adopted children to petition for open access when they reach a certain age, others only allow it in extreme medical emergencies, and others put their own legal twists on these ideas.</p>

    <p>Many people have seen viral posts on popular social media sites like Facebook where a person is holding up a sign declaring that they are looking for their biological parents or children.  Occasionally these posts even work to open up a channel of communication between involved parties, though likely they work far less often than their virality would lead you to believe.  What's needed is an updated way for parents and children to reconnect that is outside of the obstacles and sometimes prohibitive costs of the legal system.</p>
  </div>
</div>

